'''Cyber geography''' is mapping the physical network of [[broadband]] cables.<ref>[http://www.ryot.org/map-underwater-broadband-cables-google/783313 This Map of the World’s Underwater Broadband Cables Says A Lot About Who Matters], Ryot, 13 August 2014, Oliver Michaels</ref><ref> {{cite web | title = About Cyber-Geography Research | url = http://personalpages.manchester.ac.uk/staff/m.dodge/cybergeography/about.html | accessdate = 2014-08-29 }} </ref>
Further, cyber geography relates to Papadimitriou’s “Geography of Notopia”,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/13604810600982289 |title=A geography of 'Notopia' |journal=City |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=317–326 |year=2006 |last1=Papadimitriou |first1=Fivos }}</ref> that is a geographic explanation and analysis of hacking, as well as to cyber-psychology.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.chb.2009.05.009 |title=A nexus of Cyber-Geography and Cyber-Psychology: Topos/"Notopia" and identity in hacking |journal=Computers in Human Behavior |volume=25 |issue=6 |pages=1331–1334 |year=2009 |last1=Papadimitriou |first1=Fivos }}</ref>
